\[ln(P_{it}) - ln(P_{it}) \] Which in R, is implemented as diff(log(x)), as seen below.

ch_policy = ch_policy %>% 
  mutate(DATE = ymd(Week)) %>% 
  right_join(ch_temp) %>% 
  arrange(DATE) %>%
  select(-Week) %>% 
  mutate(Week = paste0(year(DATE), week(DATE))) %>% 
  group_by(Week) %>% 
  mutate(climate_change = ifelse(n() < 6, `climate change: (China)`,
        na.locf(`climate change: (China)`, fromLast = T))) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(POLICY = c(NA, diff(log(climate_change)))) %>% 
  mutate(POLICY = case_when(is.na(POLICY) ~ 0, is.nan(POLICY) ~ 0,
                            is.infinite(POLICY) ~ 0,
                            TRUE ~ POLICY))

ch_tech = ch_tech %>%

The technogology search data has a lot of weeks with 0 values, therefore calculating a change leads to many NAs, NaN (Not a Number) and infinite values, because log of zero is undefined. Consequently, these are changed to 0 for the sake of the regression, which won’t accept NA values.

3.1 Log Returns

ch_ret = ch_price %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), function(x) ifelse(x==0, NA, x))) %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), function(x) c(NA,diff(log(x))))) %>% 
  slice(-1)

R3 = ch_index %>%
  mutate(DATE = ymd(Date), `Adj Close` = as.numeric(`Adj Close`)) %>% 
  right_join(ch_temp) %>% 
  select(-c(Date, TEMP)) %>% 
  arrange(DATE) %>% 
  mutate(across(-DATE, function(x) c(NA, NA, na.locf(x)))) %>% 
  mutate(across(.cols = where(is.numeric),
                function(x) ifelse(x == 0, NA, x))) %>%
  mutate(across(.cols = where(is.numeric), function(x) c(NA,diff(log(x))))) %>%
  slice(-1)

ch_mret = ch_ret %>% 
  select(-DATE) %>% 
  rowMeans(na.rm = T) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(DATE = ch_ret$DATE) %>% 
  select(DATE, everything()) %>% 
  `colnames<-`(c("Date", "Mean"))

3.2 Market cap weighted

Portfolio return using market cap as weights. Here, market cap is proxied by volume. The individual share weight is share volume divided by total volume

w = ch_volume %>% 
  select(-...412) %>%
  mutate(DATE = as.Date(Date, origin = "1899-12-31")) %>% 
  select(DATE, everything()) %>% 
  right_join(ch_temp) %>% 
  arrange(DATE) %>% 
  select(-c(Date, TEMP)) %>%
  select(DATE, everything()) %>% 
  slice(-1)

w[, -1] = w[, -1] / rowSums(w[, -1], na.rm = T)

The portfolio return is the average of the return multiplied by the weights.

ch_mret_cap = rowMeans(ch_ret[, -1] * w[, -1], na.rm = T) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(DATE = ch_ret$DATE) %>% 
  select(DATE, everything()) %>% 
  `colnames<-`(c("Date", "Mean"))

3.3 Abnormal Returns

The abnormal returns is simply the difference between portfolio return and index return.

ch_ar <- ch_mret %>% 
  left_join(R3, by = c("Date"="DATE")) %>% 
  mutate(AR = Mean - `Adj Close`)

ch_ar_cap <- ch_mret_cap %>% 
  left_join(R3, by = c("Date"="DATE")) %>% 
  mutate(AR_c = Mean - `Adj Close`) %>% 
  rename(DATE = Date)
regdata_eq1 <- ch_ar %>% 
  rename(DATE = Date) %>% 
  select(DATE, AR) %>% 
  left_join(ch_temp) %>% 
  left_join(ch_policy) %>% 
  left_join(ch_tech) %>% 
  left_join(ch_ar_cap) %>% 
  select(AR, AR_c, TEMP, POLICY, TECH, DATE) %>% 
  mutate(across(.cols = -DATE, function(x) ifelse(is.nan(x), NA, 
                                                  ifelse(is.infinite(x), NA, x))))

eq1 <- lm(AR ~ TEMP + POLICY + TECH, data = regdata_eq1)

eq1_cap <- lm(AR_c ~ TEMP + POLICY + TECH, data = regdata_eq1)

coefs = coefs %>% 
  pivot_wider(id_cols = Date) %>% 
  select(-Date)

t.test.list = lapply(coefs, t.test)

t.results <- data.frame(
  series = colnames(coefs), 
  xsquared = sapply(t.test.list, "[[", "statistic"), 
  pvalue = sapply(t.test.list, "[[", "p.value")
)
